^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about the play first. Once the opening lead is made, Anna can count 4 club tricks and two tricks in each of the other suits for a total of at least 10 tricks. She can also count on a third spade trick, no matter who has the Queen. And, if the diamond finesse works, she can count on three diamond tricks. Anyway, Anna has 11 tricks for sure, and possibly 12. So, her best line is probably King then Jack of spades which sets up an extra spade for her. Then she can take the diamond finesse, since she still has double stoppers in all suits and can end up with 12 tricks.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That is a better line than trying to set up hearts, which requires a 3-3 break. Remember, 3-3 breaks are less likely than 4-2 breaks. The general rule about suits breaking is:|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If there are an odd number of cards out, the suits tend to break as evenly as possible. So, if you have an 8 card fit, the most likely break of the outstanding 5 cards is 3-2. But if you have an even number of cards out, the most likely break is not an even break. If you have a nine card fit, 2-2 is not the most likely break, 3-1 is more likely. With a 7-card fit, 3-3 is not the most likely break, 4-2 is. You do not need to know the exact odds. The important thing to remember is that with even number of cards out, an even break is not that likely. You should not count on it unless that is the only way to make the hand.|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now back to Puppet Stayman. It is used over 2N openers, and 2C followed by 2N rebids (which, as I said before, is essentially the same thing). Opener often has a 5 card major in these auctions. So, Puppet Stayman allows you to discover both 4-4 fits, and 5-3 fits if opener has the 5 card major. It works as follows.
With a 5 card major, opener bids her major, as Anna did.
With a 4 card major, opener bids 3D, which specifically shows one or both 4 card majors.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If opener has no 4 or 5 card major, she bids 3N.
Now, if opener bids 3D, and responder has a 4 card major, it gets a bit tricky because the idea is, you want the opener (the strong hand) to be the declarer. If responder has a 4 card major, she does not want to bid that major and be declarer so, responder bids the other major.
The auction 2N-3C-3D-3S, for example, means responder has 4 hearts. Then, if the 2N opener has 4 hearts, she can then bid 4H. If she has 4 spades she can bid 3N.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Similarly if responder has spades, the auction goes 2N-3C-3D-3H where 2N opener bids 4S with four spades and 3N with four hearts. Further, if responder has both majors, then she knows they must have a fit then she bids 4D. Thus, the auction 2N-3C-3D-4D shows both 4-card majors in responder's hand and opener bids her 4 card major. It sounds complicated, but if you practice it a little bit, it makes sense. Having said that, I do not play Puppet with my wife Ava, and we have not missed it, lol. So, if you want to skip Puppet, it probably won't hurt your bridge. BTW, all Puppet bids are alerted.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


