^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about the auction first. I got a question about should Elizabeth (when she was sitting South) bid Stayman. Playing normal Stayman, you need at least an invitational hand to bid Stayman. In general, you should not bid Stayman unless you have at least 8 points. Therefore, the 2D transfer was a good bid on this hand. There is a variation of Stayman that I play, which I like. I am sure that most of you know about Garbage Stayman. That is where responder is short in clubs, and has long diamonds and at least 3 cards in each of the majors and a weak hand. With that hand, responder passes whatever the response is to Stayman. With a weak hand, and short clubs, normally it is better to play in a suit. |
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is a variation of Garbage Stayman that I like, and it comes up quite a bit. I play if the auction goes 1N-2C-2D-2H, that is also Garbage Stayman but it shows at least 4 cards in each major. The 1N opener is supposed to pass with better hearts, and correct to spades with better spades. Had Elizabeth been playing that version of Garbage Stayman, she could have bid 2C. In that case the auction goes, 1N-2C-2D-2H-P. And if North happened to have longer/better spades, North would correct to 2S. I am not saying you should play it, but I happen to like it. However, you better agree with your partner before trying it.|
