NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play although I don't like doubleton leads, Anna really has no good choice other than clubs. She might lead a spade hoping partner has the Queen or Ace, but that is risky and does not work well on this hand as it turns out. |
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Once Kia gets a club lead, he should probably think about setting up dummy. If he plays another club at trick 2, basically, he will lose 1 diamond and 1 club and make 5. So, that is the best line on this hand: just play another club. Most players have a hard time visualizing setting up dummy. But it is a good thing to keep in mind.  |
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I did a bridge puzzle a while ago. I presented a hand, asked people how they would play it, and most everyone made it. Then a couple of months later, I gave the same hand, except I reversed dummy and declarer, and most people went down. So, there is some interesting psychology there. Most people find it easier to set up declarer's hand than dummy. If you can learn to look at both hands equally, you will improve your play, as this hand illustrates.|
